This course will give you an in-depth introduction to the complicated bundle of ties and tensions between Russia and Ukraine. It will also open a window onto the unique history of the rich multi-ethnic culture of Ukraine, its unique musical traditions, and the story of its centuries-long search for a national identity. 
The seminar will start from the discussion of current events in August 2014 –– i.e., post-EuroMaidan and post-annexation of Crimea.  During the first week of classes, we will read various Western news reports on Russian-Ukrainian relations, the role of the West, and we will record our conclusions at that initial level of our engagement with the country.  Then we will step by step cover the following topics: 

Overview of Ukrainian history;
Ukraine's multi-ethnic population today;
The Story of the Cossacks in Ukraine and Elsewhere;
dumas);
The Making of Ukrainian Jew/Life in a shtetl;
Controversy of Stepan Bandera and Ukrainian Insurgent Army;
Artificially Created Famine of the 1930s (Holodomor);
From 2004 "Orange Revolution" to 2013 Maidan.  

In the last week, we will re-visit the current events, and see whether our interpretation of these will have changed as the result of our studies.
All readings will be in English, no knowledge of Russian or Ukrainian is required.  In addition to readings, we will screen several films and several times through semester will establish real-time skype connections to artists and intellectuals in Kiev, Ukraine. This course counts towards the Russian and Eastern European Studies Minor.

In this course, students will learn how to:

Converse on common topics such as sports, politics, religion, health, food, weather, shopping, and news;
Begin and end conversations, request clarification, interrupt and take turns, change the subject, give feedback, tell stories, run meetings, and make presentations;
Use common ASL structures such as topic/comment, scene-setting, and temporal sequencing; and
Communicate in various circumstances, such as using English word order, voicing while signing, interpreting in informal situations, conversing with deaf-blind people.

There are no exams. Grades are based on consistent attendance and participation, mastery of the material as demonstrated in short written assignments, simulations, skits, and presentations (individually and in groups), and assigned out-of-class activities.

